But let's look at nucleation.

00:12:42.120 --> 00:12:45.480
What happens between months and
seconds before the earthquake?

00:12:45.480 --> 00:12:48.860
Unfortunately, all of
these precautionary phases

00:12:48.860 --> 00:12:53.010
are seen or detected
after the earthquake.

00:12:53.010 --> 00:12:55.350
So far, we have
seen those phases,

00:12:55.350 --> 00:12:59.050
but it's always after going
back to looking at the data.

00:12:59.050 --> 00:13:05.470
So in 2011, March 29, 2011,
magnitude 9.0 in Japan.

00:13:05.470 --> 00:13:07.090
This is a map of Japan.

00:13:07.090 --> 00:13:11.880
This plot is showing you with
colors the amount of slip

00:13:11.880 --> 00:13:14.360
on a fault surface.

00:13:14.360 --> 00:13:16.080
It's dipping like this.

00:13:16.080 --> 00:13:17.940
And the contours are
showing you where

00:13:17.940 --> 00:13:20.694
the slip during the
Tohoku event happened.

00:13:20.694 --> 00:13:22.110
So basically in
the middle, that's

00:13:22.110 --> 00:13:25.050
where you had about
15 meters of slip

00:13:25.050 --> 00:13:26.740
and then nothing in between.

00:13:26.740 --> 00:13:28.140
And these colors
are showing what

00:13:28.140 --> 00:13:30.540
happened before the earthquake.

00:13:30.540 --> 00:13:33.680
And so using data
on shore, scientists

00:13:33.680 --> 00:13:37.970
have been able to look at how
much slip, very slow slip,

00:13:37.970 --> 00:13:41.570
happened years before
the earthquake.

00:13:41.570 --> 00:13:44.090
This line here,
this time series,

00:13:44.090 --> 00:13:49.130
is showing you what a GPS would
record as a function of years.

00:13:49.130 --> 00:13:51.500
So you can see we
don't have that many,

00:13:51.500 --> 00:13:54.640
we have maybe a few
decades worth of data,

00:13:54.640 --> 00:13:56.190
but not that much more.

00:13:56.190 --> 00:13:57.920
And if you remove
some of the effects,

00:13:57.920 --> 00:14:01.400
you can see that there is this
non-constant but accelerating

00:14:01.400 --> 00:14:06.020
phase of displacement, and
this is mapped into the fault.

00:14:06.020 --> 00:14:08.120
And so we have this
acceleration of slip,

00:14:08.120 --> 00:14:12.860
it's very slow and
steady, but it grows.

00:14:12.860 --> 00:14:15.770
And we can detect it by
looking at years of data.

00:14:15.770 --> 00:14:21.110
It's very often afterwards
that we notice this.

00:14:21.110 --> 00:14:23.810
If you look at the foreshocks.

00:14:23.810 --> 00:14:27.710
Foreshocks are earthquakes that
happened before the earthquake,

00:14:27.710 --> 00:14:29.030
the main shock.

00:14:29.030 --> 00:14:31.130
Foreshocks are only
called foreshocks

00:14:31.130 --> 00:14:34.400
after the main shock,
so it's hard to use them

00:14:34.400 --> 00:14:36.564
as a prediction.

00:14:36.564 --> 00:14:38.480
What I'm showing you
here is three earthquakes

00:14:38.480 --> 00:14:41.280
that happened in
Southern California.

00:14:41.280 --> 00:14:44.370
This is the El Mayor-Cucapah
earthquake in 2010.

00:14:44.370 --> 00:14:47.630
I have sensors actually nearby.

00:14:47.630 --> 00:14:50.390
And my husband actually
was on a Jeep on the road

00:14:50.390 --> 00:14:54.140
with GPS deploying
sensors at the same time.

00:14:54.140 --> 00:14:56.300
These are two
earthquakes in the 90s

00:14:56.300 --> 00:15:00.060
that happened on the eastern
shore zone in California.

00:15:00.060 --> 00:15:01.850
These are showing
you the magnitude

00:15:01.850 --> 00:15:04.130
with time of the earthquakes.

00:15:04.130 --> 00:15:07.820
The black ones are, you
see the aftershocks.

00:15:07.820 --> 00:15:10.160
because they happen
after the main shock,

00:15:10.160 --> 00:15:11.720
shown with this cross.

00:15:11.720 --> 00:15:14.416
And the red ones
are the foreshocks.

00:15:14.416 --> 00:15:17.050
Do you see any pattern?

00:15:17.050 --> 00:15:17.550
No.

00:15:17.550 --> 00:15:19.080
There are some
earthquakes, but are they

00:15:19.080 --> 00:15:21.360
foreshocks, aftershocks of
the previous earthquakes?

00:15:21.360 --> 00:15:22.690
We don't know.

00:15:22.690 --> 00:15:24.390
So these are kind
of the observations.

00:15:24.390 --> 00:15:27.660
In the lab though, if you were
to make earthquakes in the lab,

00:15:27.660 --> 00:15:30.210
the system is a lot
more predictable.

00:15:30.210 --> 00:15:34.810
And so these lab quakes,
they win every time.

00:15:34.810 --> 00:15:36.010
I'll show you at the end.

00:15:36.010 --> 00:15:37.900
We have a nice plot on this.

00:15:37.900 --> 00:15:40.960
These lab quakes
behave so nicely.

00:15:40.960 --> 00:15:44.530
They behave like the model,
not like the Earth, apparently.

00:15:44.530 --> 00:15:48.530
But these lab quakes are showing
you the onset of seismicity.

00:15:48.530 --> 00:15:50.800
You can see those dots,
same kind of style

00:15:50.800 --> 00:15:53.290
here, getting more
and more frequent

00:15:53.290 --> 00:15:55.624
as we go, right
before the earthquake.

00:15:55.624 --> 00:15:57.790
And this is just showing
you kind of an acceleration

00:15:57.790 --> 00:15:59.410
of the step on the earthquakes.

00:15:59.410 --> 00:16:02.410
So in the lab, they behave
like we want them to be.

00:16:02.410 --> 00:16:06.690
In nature, it's just
not, it's not there yet.

00:16:06.690 --> 00:16:11.400
And there are two debated models
for how earthquakes start,

00:16:11.400 --> 00:16:15.420
and no one, I think, has clearly
stated this is the one model.

00:16:15.420 --> 00:16:18.120
I think it's probably, as
always, a combination of both.

00:16:18.120 --> 00:16:18.840
.

00:16:18.840 --> 00:16:21.600
These are the
cascade model, where

00:16:21.600 --> 00:16:24.540
you have a bunch of
pops on the fault.

00:16:24.540 --> 00:16:26.130
They all pop and
trigger each other

00:16:26.130 --> 00:16:29.320
and then eventually becomes
a big one, in which case

00:16:29.320 --> 00:16:30.820
it's very hard to
say which one is

00:16:30.820 --> 00:16:32.860
going to trigger the last one.

00:16:32.860 --> 00:16:35.470
Or you can have
this one, which is

00:16:35.470 --> 00:16:39.820
kind of a slow growth, a seismic
slip which accelerates and then

00:16:39.820 --> 00:16:41.380
becomes a big one.

00:16:41.380 --> 00:16:44.300
And this is rarely observed.

00:16:44.300 --> 00:16:45.520
And like this one.

00:16:45.520 --> 00:16:48.940
But it's a lot more
consistent with models and lab

00:16:48.940 --> 00:16:50.200
experiments.

00:16:50.200 --> 00:16:52.780
And so there were many
papers this summer

00:16:52.780 --> 00:16:55.270
that discuss these two
models, and then we

00:16:55.270 --> 00:16:58.550
don't have the data resolution
to actually validate those two.

00:16:58.550 --> 00:17:00.620
But this is the grail of
earthquake prediction.

00:17:00.620 --> 00:17:05.210
If you could actually see those
eventually and classify them

00:17:05.210 --> 00:17:07.160
as precursor, then
maybe you would

00:17:07.160 --> 00:17:10.760
be able to be before
the earthquake.

00:17:10.760 --> 00:17:13.780
So I would say that what
happened in nucleation,

00:17:13.780 --> 00:17:16.630
I think maybe we rarely
observe them, usually

00:17:16.630 --> 00:17:18.099
for large earthquakes.

00:17:18.099 --> 00:17:21.190
But we have observed some.

00:17:21.190 --> 00:17:23.140
So I think looking
back at the data,

00:17:23.140 --> 00:17:28.069
we may have hope to study
those phases a lot more.

00:17:28.069 --> 00:17:31.830
So now, the user, the
person, the surgeon,

00:17:31.830 --> 00:17:34.500
the eye surgeon with
his laser is saying,

00:17:34.500 --> 00:17:37.320
when should I stop the laser?

00:17:37.320 --> 00:17:40.330
When is the shaking coming
if there is an earthquake?

00:17:40.330 --> 00:17:42.390
And so, I'm not
skipping this phase,

00:17:42.390 --> 00:17:46.380
I'm just saying, who cares about
when the earthquake happened?

00:17:46.380 --> 00:17:49.920
I really care just about the
shaking and how much shaking.

00:17:49.920 --> 00:17:52.320
And this becomes
actually a different side

00:17:52.320 --> 00:17:56.940
of seismology, which is very
much oriented toward operation

00:17:56.940 --> 00:18:00.390
and user and, you know,
what matters for people

00:18:00.390 --> 00:18:02.940
is really just the amount of
shaking, whatever earthquake

00:18:02.940 --> 00:18:04.590
style we have.

00:18:04.590 --> 00:18:07.800
So, if these are your
science question,

00:18:07.800 --> 00:18:10.780
then we can look
at other things.

00:18:10.780 --> 00:18:14.940
So I want to focus the
rest of this discussion

00:18:14.940 --> 00:18:19.140
on what happened during the
rupture and right after,

00:18:19.140 --> 00:18:24.120
and how can we help the
early warning of the shaking.

00:18:24.120 --> 00:18:25.620
And this is--

00:18:25.620 --> 00:18:28.620
I'm an amateur at this, but
I wanted to show you briefly

00:18:28.620 --> 00:18:30.990
what the system of the
earthquake early warning

00:18:30.990 --> 00:18:32.120
is about.

00:18:32.120 --> 00:18:33.960
And I heard today
that the funding

00:18:33.960 --> 00:18:37.320
will be continued, which
is nice when you already

00:18:37.320 --> 00:18:40.680
spent 20 millions of
dollars, to have it finally

00:18:40.680 --> 00:18:43.360
an official earthquake early
warning system in the United

00:18:43.360 --> 00:18:44.890
States.

00:18:44.890 --> 00:18:47.950
Mexico has one since the 90s.

00:18:47.950 --> 00:18:49.990
So we're developing--

00:18:49.990 --> 00:18:53.840
Scientists are developing
one in California,

00:18:53.840 --> 00:18:55.730
and we'll see the
West Coast in general.

00:18:55.730 --> 00:18:58.270
And the system is as such.

00:18:58.270 --> 00:19:02.800
Phones and internet is
faster, propagates faster,

00:19:02.800 --> 00:19:04.510
than seismic waves.

00:19:04.510 --> 00:19:05.830
That's where you win.

00:19:05.830 --> 00:19:07.420
That's basically it.

00:19:07.420 --> 00:19:10.620
If you have an earthquake
that happens on a fault,

00:19:10.620 --> 00:19:11.910
some ways will propagate.

00:19:11.910 --> 00:19:13.860
The first one, the yellow one.

00:19:13.860 --> 00:19:15.810
The first one is not
the most damaging,

00:19:15.810 --> 00:19:18.100
but he carries a
lot of information.

00:19:18.100 --> 00:19:23.730
So what you want is having
sensors close by the epicenter.

00:19:23.730 --> 00:19:26.340
Then you have more to say well,
this is an earthquake and not

00:19:26.340 --> 00:19:29.580
a car driving by, so you may
need a few sensors for this.

00:19:29.580 --> 00:19:33.150
But then the information is no
longer sent with seismic waves,

00:19:33.150 --> 00:19:37.160
but with phones and
communication like this,

00:19:37.160 --> 00:19:41.520
so then the data gets into
the earthquake [INAUDIBLE],,

00:19:41.520 --> 00:19:43.500
and then there's a
decision-making module which

00:19:43.500 --> 00:19:45.960
says, this will be the
size of the earthquake,

00:19:45.960 --> 00:19:47.850
therefore this will
be the shaking.

00:19:47.850 --> 00:19:49.470
Should we alert, yes, no.

00:19:49.470 --> 00:19:53.550
All of these modules are quite
complicated and elaborated.

00:19:53.550 --> 00:19:55.170
And then it gets to the people.

00:19:55.170 --> 00:19:56.670
And there are apps,
you can have it

00:19:56.670 --> 00:19:58.980
on your phone that
would tell you

00:19:58.980 --> 00:20:01.710
the level of shaking of
intensity of such will arrive

00:20:01.710 --> 00:20:05.220
at x seconds, or in x seconds.

00:20:05.220 --> 00:20:07.770
So the basis for the
earthquake early warning,

00:20:07.770 --> 00:20:12.030
it's not to say the
earthquake will happen.

00:20:12.030 --> 00:20:14.820
It's to say an
earthquake has happened,

00:20:14.820 --> 00:20:18.270
now the shaking will
happen in such time.

00:20:18.270 --> 00:20:21.150
So you can already see
that the further away you

00:20:21.150 --> 00:20:27.090
are from the fault, the greater
advance knowledge you may have.

00:20:27.090 --> 00:20:29.490
If you're very
close to the faults,

00:20:29.490 --> 00:20:31.740
you may not have a
second of warning.

00:20:31.740 --> 00:20:35.220
So this is not even a point
almost of having warning.

00:20:35.220 --> 00:20:37.170
Although I'd like to say
that that one second,

00:20:37.170 --> 00:20:39.810
and I always think
about this eye surgeon

00:20:39.810 --> 00:20:42.750
with a laser in your eye,
and maybe that one second

00:20:42.750 --> 00:20:45.120
we'll just shut off the
laser and that might actually

00:20:45.120 --> 00:20:46.230
save your eye.

00:20:46.230 --> 00:20:48.720
So even one second is important.

00:20:48.720 --> 00:20:52.860
In Japan, in the
nuclear power plant,

00:20:52.860 --> 00:20:56.100
they have seismometers
three kilometers down.

00:20:56.100 --> 00:21:00.780
And this three kilometers down
with a 3 kilometers per second,

00:21:00.780 --> 00:21:03.300
wave speed, gives you
one second warning,

00:21:03.300 --> 00:21:06.840
is sufficient to shut
down the operations.

00:21:06.840 --> 00:21:11.470
So even those few
seconds matter.

00:21:11.470 --> 00:21:16.980
But for the person, you and
I, or [INAUDIBLE] next week,

00:21:16.980 --> 00:21:22.500
sorry, you might want
some level of warning.

00:21:22.500 --> 00:21:24.510
And so a lot of
the questions have

00:21:24.510 --> 00:21:26.820
been if the earthquake
just happened,

00:21:26.820 --> 00:21:31.650
it may last tens of seconds,
maybe 30, 70 seconds.

00:21:31.650 --> 00:21:33.181
As soon as the
earthquake happens,

00:21:33.181 --> 00:21:34.680
I want to know how
big it is, I want

00:21:34.680 --> 00:21:36.600
to know how much shaking it is.

00:21:36.600 --> 00:21:39.060
Because the longer we
wait for that warning,

00:21:39.060 --> 00:21:40.710
the less Warning we'll have.

00:21:40.710 --> 00:21:45.910
And so a lot of the questions
have been both in the--

00:21:45.910 --> 00:21:47.970
the use of data for
earthquake early warning,

00:21:47.970 --> 00:21:50.190
but in terms of
physics of earthquakes,

00:21:50.190 --> 00:21:53.760
is this beginning pulse,
this beginning onset,

00:21:53.760 --> 00:21:57.620
will carry the information
of the size of the event.

00:21:57.620 --> 00:22:00.630
Another way to say
this is we call that

00:22:00.630 --> 00:22:02.840
the determinism in earthquakes.

00:22:02.840 --> 00:22:04.784
Is the beginning
of the earthquake

00:22:04.784 --> 00:22:06.200
carries enough
information that we

00:22:06.200 --> 00:22:08.720
know what the end of the
earthquake is going to be like,

00:22:08.720 --> 00:22:10.520
therefore we can
tell what magnitude,

00:22:10.520 --> 00:22:13.412
therefore we can tell
what type of shaking.

00:22:13.412 --> 00:22:14.870
And so a lot of
the questions are--

00:22:14.870 --> 00:22:18.080
There's a lot of
skepticism, again related

00:22:18.080 --> 00:22:21.500
to this Parkfield failed
experiment about earthquake

00:22:21.500 --> 00:22:22.850
determinism.

00:22:22.850 --> 00:22:26.510
And so in publications,
I was recommended

00:22:26.510 --> 00:22:30.140
to not use this term, it's
politically not correct.

00:22:30.140 --> 00:22:32.800
But all it says is
there any information

00:22:32.800 --> 00:22:36.880
at the beginning that tells us
the evolution of earthquake?

00:22:36.880 --> 00:22:40.750
And so it's just a word, and
I think there are sides to it,

00:22:40.750 --> 00:22:43.980
and I'm showing
you the both sides.

00:22:43.980 --> 00:22:48.600
And we'll take one side, we'll
see at the end of this talk.

00:22:48.600 --> 00:22:50.760
But basically there
are two camps,

00:22:50.760 --> 00:22:52.410
that's why we have debates.

00:22:52.410 --> 00:22:56.440
They are the camp that say yes,
earthquakes are deterministic.

00:22:56.440 --> 00:22:58.930
If we look at the
onset of earthquakes,

00:22:58.930 --> 00:23:01.050
I know what the final
size of the earthquake

00:23:01.050 --> 00:23:03.510
will be before it even ends.

00:23:03.510 --> 00:23:06.280
And then you have the
no camp, which says

00:23:06.280 --> 00:23:08.330
look, all earthquakes look--

00:23:08.330 --> 00:23:10.130
[INAUDIBLE] this
started the same way.

00:23:10.130 --> 00:23:12.050
And I'll explain those plots.

00:23:12.050 --> 00:23:13.710
But the bottom line
is that we have

00:23:13.710 --> 00:23:17.160
different data, different
ways to process it,

00:23:17.160 --> 00:23:18.900
different school of thinking.

00:23:18.900 --> 00:23:24.300
Those are probably the same
earthquakes and we're just--

00:23:24.300 --> 00:23:27.210
we're not coordinated enough
to be very systematic yet

00:23:27.210 --> 00:23:32.570
in our approaches to analyze the
data in a very objective way.

00:23:32.570 --> 00:23:34.850
So on this camp,
these are plots that

00:23:34.850 --> 00:23:39.190
show time of the earthquakes
to some normalization.

00:23:39.190 --> 00:23:43.600
This is in log scale of the
peak ground displacement.

00:23:43.600 --> 00:23:44.530
And the blue--

00:23:44.530 --> 00:23:47.770
The colors are showing you the
magnitude of the earthquake.

00:23:47.770 --> 00:23:52.090
And basically you see that
the way the displacement grows

00:23:52.090 --> 00:23:55.540
with time is not the
same for magnitude 9

00:23:55.540 --> 00:23:57.940
or a magnitude 4 Others say--

00:23:57.940 --> 00:24:03.100
This is a 2014 study that said
small earthquakes start faster

00:24:03.100 --> 00:24:04.880
than big earthquakes.

00:24:07.820 --> 00:24:09.650
This study actually
shows the opposite,

00:24:09.650 --> 00:24:11.420
so I'm not sure the
validity of this.

00:24:11.420 --> 00:24:16.100
But still, it's about
this growth, basically.

00:24:16.100 --> 00:24:19.010
This group shows
that in [INAUDIBLE]..

00:24:19.010 --> 00:24:23.270
By the way, in earth science,
we have so many scales

00:24:23.270 --> 00:24:27.470
that we put everything in
log time, spatial scales.

00:24:27.470 --> 00:24:31.040
We like to collapse things
into this lab log scale.

00:24:31.040 --> 00:24:36.630
So this is the log of the peak
ground displacement in meters.

00:24:36.630 --> 00:24:40.040
This is the log since
the P wave started.

00:24:40.040 --> 00:24:41.810
And so you can see
these are bandwidth

00:24:41.810 --> 00:24:44.120
with earthquake magnitudes.

00:24:44.120 --> 00:24:46.130
You have a lot of--

00:24:46.130 --> 00:24:49.710
I don't think we're really
good statistics, to be honest.

00:24:49.710 --> 00:24:51.870
Because we think that
everything is log normal,

00:24:51.870 --> 00:24:54.350
so we think median and means
and we try to respect this

00:24:54.350 --> 00:24:58.120
but it's not necessarily robust.

00:24:58.120 --> 00:25:01.580
Nonetheless, if we take
the median of these curves,

00:25:01.580 --> 00:25:04.804
of P waves, which are the
first waves that arrive,

00:25:04.804 --> 00:25:07.220
you can see that the beginning,
whatever the magnitude you

00:25:07.220 --> 00:25:09.940
are at, the kind of
look one in the same.

00:25:09.940 --> 00:25:12.620
But this is one data
set, this is one team.

00:25:12.620 --> 00:25:15.820
These guys are saying, I'm using
another data, I don't see this,

00:25:15.820 --> 00:25:18.460
and debate goes
on and on and on.

00:25:18.460 --> 00:25:20.920
And so, it's really
interesting to think

00:25:20.920 --> 00:25:24.080
about there's a lot of
diversity in earthquake

00:25:24.080 --> 00:25:26.360
and so really, how
should we study them?

00:25:26.360 --> 00:25:28.870
We have all these scales
and [INAUDIBLE] scales

00:25:28.870 --> 00:25:32.280
and temporal scales
and so, I think

00:25:32.280 --> 00:25:34.030
we're not really
fully integrated yet,

00:25:34.030 --> 00:25:37.720
but I think there's
hope to do that.

00:25:37.720 --> 00:25:39.892
I'm not yet fully
integrated, but I'm just

00:25:39.892 --> 00:25:42.100
raising the question and I
think eventually we should

00:25:42.100 --> 00:25:45.190
think about all the scales.

00:25:45.190 --> 00:25:49.550
And so-- pardon for the
