00:28:58.170 --> 00:29:00.705
I'm happy to talk more
details about that later.

00:29:00.705 --> 00:29:02.580
And I'm showing you two
types of earthquakes.

00:29:02.580 --> 00:29:07.050
We have the big one in orange,
the small one in turquoise,

00:29:07.050 --> 00:29:09.750
teal, beautiful color scheme.

00:29:09.750 --> 00:29:11.080
And they look different, right?

00:29:11.080 --> 00:29:13.860
So one is really
complex, lots of bumps.

00:29:13.860 --> 00:29:15.690
They're not the simple
triangle function.

00:29:15.690 --> 00:29:17.273
If you look at
individual earthquakes,

00:29:17.273 --> 00:29:19.590
there are a lot
of richness in it.

00:29:19.590 --> 00:29:21.940
And then the small
one has one bump.

00:29:21.940 --> 00:29:26.330
And so he basically said,
let's count the bumps.

00:29:26.330 --> 00:29:30.650
And he made bumps with
Gaussian functions, lognormal,

00:29:30.650 --> 00:29:33.200
we love it, and he
composed these functions

00:29:33.200 --> 00:29:36.770
by just adding and summing
all of these log functions

00:29:36.770 --> 00:29:40.550
and counting them as
what we called subevents.

00:29:40.550 --> 00:29:42.350
They are not a full
earthquake, they're

00:29:42.350 --> 00:29:45.380
just a small earthquake,
a small event

00:29:45.380 --> 00:29:48.290
that belongs to the earthquake.

00:29:48.290 --> 00:29:50.680
And so it seems like
large earthquakes have

00:29:50.680 --> 00:29:54.455
a lot of bumps, subevents,
and small earthquakes

00:29:54.455 --> 00:29:56.050
have fewer bumps.

00:29:56.050 --> 00:29:59.410
So that's increased complexity
with earthquake size,

00:29:59.410 --> 00:30:02.360
which is not that surprising.

00:30:02.360 --> 00:30:06.320
What was interesting is we could
model this very simply in-house

00:30:06.320 --> 00:30:10.480
with simple fracture
mechanics models,

00:30:10.480 --> 00:30:13.810
where we created earthquakes
with a set of parameters

00:30:13.810 --> 00:30:14.909
I can explain later.

00:30:14.909 --> 00:30:17.200
But basically what we found
is the big earthquakes that

00:30:17.200 --> 00:30:21.630
a lot of bumps and the
small earthquakes--

00:30:21.630 --> 00:30:24.060
smaller earthquake has one bump.

00:30:24.060 --> 00:30:25.060
OK.

00:30:25.060 --> 00:30:27.280
So the number of
bumps or some subevent

00:30:27.280 --> 00:30:29.500
grows with earthquake size.

00:30:29.500 --> 00:30:31.990
This x-axis here is
showing you the size

00:30:31.990 --> 00:30:34.360
of the main event,
the main shock,

00:30:34.360 --> 00:30:37.600
and these are the
number of subevents.

00:30:37.600 --> 00:30:41.490
You can see that with
growing size, this is Tohoku,

00:30:41.490 --> 00:30:45.520
and by all means, an outlier for
everybody to study earthquakes,

00:30:45.520 --> 00:30:47.300
but the biggest
one is the outlier.

00:30:47.300 --> 00:30:51.820
But if you look at ensemble
of the number of subevents,

00:30:51.820 --> 00:30:54.220
you have a growing
number of subevents.

00:30:54.220 --> 00:30:56.290
So big earthquakes
are more complex

00:30:56.290 --> 00:30:58.540
because they have
more subevents.

00:30:58.540 --> 00:31:03.200
However, it's not we don't
have a log scale here.

00:31:03.200 --> 00:31:05.250
And so actually, the
size of the subevents

00:31:05.250 --> 00:31:08.160
grows also with the
size of the earthquake.

00:31:08.160 --> 00:31:10.350
And that was really
the breakthrough,

00:31:10.350 --> 00:31:13.320
is that we don't have a
characteristic bump that

00:31:13.320 --> 00:31:16.320
tells us a characteristic
length scale in the earth.

00:31:16.320 --> 00:31:18.050
Instead the earthquake
dynamics has

00:31:18.050 --> 00:31:22.170
this interesting and
intrinsic link scale

00:31:22.170 --> 00:31:24.810
that is characteristic
to the earthquake's size.

00:31:24.810 --> 00:31:27.780
All of these dots
are a subevent that

00:31:27.780 --> 00:31:31.440
has a size shown in here
in log scale attached

00:31:31.440 --> 00:31:34.840
to the size of the main
earthquake shown here.

00:31:34.840 --> 00:31:36.870
These lines, this
is a one to one

00:31:36.870 --> 00:31:40.620
line saying the subevent
here has the same size

00:31:40.620 --> 00:31:44.850
as its master
earthquake, in which case

00:31:44.850 --> 00:31:48.870
this earthquake probably only
has one subevent to form it.

00:31:48.870 --> 00:31:51.660
This line here is showing
you that earthquakes

00:31:51.660 --> 00:31:54.630
would have about 100
bumps, 100 subevents,

00:31:54.630 --> 00:31:57.000
to form the earthquake.

00:31:57.000 --> 00:31:59.970
And so what you can see, it
is not an infinite amount.

00:31:59.970 --> 00:32:02.250
The subevents don't
have the same size.

00:32:02.250 --> 00:32:05.940
These events actually grow
with earthquake magnitude.

00:32:05.940 --> 00:32:07.930
And so what was interesting,
the current scale

00:32:07.930 --> 00:32:11.920
is representing
the distribution.

00:32:11.920 --> 00:32:14.770
And so, these small
events tend to have

00:32:14.770 --> 00:32:19.330
mostly one main subevent,
versus the large event

00:32:19.330 --> 00:32:21.190
have a lot more.

00:32:21.190 --> 00:32:24.130
And if you were to
draw kind of a scaling,

00:32:24.130 --> 00:32:28.521
it's not one to one but
some very strong scaling.

00:32:28.521 --> 00:32:30.770
So that means in terms of
structure of the earthquake,

00:32:30.770 --> 00:32:33.890
a small event has a small
bump and the big event

00:32:33.890 --> 00:32:36.480
has a big bump at the beginning.

00:32:36.480 --> 00:32:40.340
So let's say you measure
this, you can tell crudely

00:32:40.340 --> 00:32:44.170
what size of the earthquake
it is, which is fine,

00:32:44.170 --> 00:32:45.327
the earthquake is done.

00:32:45.327 --> 00:32:47.035
But if you go to those
larger magnitudes,

00:32:47.035 --> 00:32:49.450
if you measure this
first bump, then you

00:32:49.450 --> 00:32:53.720
can predict or estimate the
final size of the event.

00:32:53.720 --> 00:32:56.210
Without the earthquake, the
earthquake is not done yet,

00:32:56.210 --> 00:33:01.060
you're just making an inference
based on this organization

00:33:01.060 --> 00:33:04.280
of the seismic signal.

00:33:04.280 --> 00:33:06.760
And so we took this
independent data set,

00:33:06.760 --> 00:33:09.930
we looked at this recent
Indonesia earthquake

00:33:09.930 --> 00:33:12.720
in 2018, 7.5.

