is close to failure,

00:38:47.060 --> 00:38:50.750
you may have some of those
more impulsive events.

00:38:50.750 --> 00:38:52.460
But what was interesting
is they managed

00:38:52.460 --> 00:38:56.030
to using this
ambient time series

00:38:56.030 --> 00:39:00.110
to predict the time to
failure through time here

00:39:00.110 --> 00:39:01.590
during the experiment.

00:39:01.590 --> 00:39:04.700
And so their prediction
was shown in blue,

00:39:04.700 --> 00:39:06.380
with a random first algorithm.

00:39:06.380 --> 00:39:08.690
And then what the
experimental data was showing

00:39:08.690 --> 00:39:10.045
is shown in red.

00:39:10.045 --> 00:39:12.650
And these are the
validation part.

00:39:12.650 --> 00:39:16.190
And so it's really stunning that
even though it's not regular,

00:39:16.190 --> 00:39:20.300
these predictions were able
to show a weaker earthquake

00:39:20.300 --> 00:39:22.350
compared to a big earthquake.

00:39:22.350 --> 00:39:26.090
So I thought it was one of
the most promising study

00:39:26.090 --> 00:39:29.500
for machine learning
to predict earthquakes.

00:39:29.500 --> 00:39:32.850
In-house, our team
at Harvard has

00:39:32.850 --> 00:39:37.566
been able to predict the
location of aftershocks.

00:39:37.566 --> 00:39:39.690
And so as I was telling
you, we have the main shock

00:39:39.690 --> 00:39:41.730
and then we have many
aftershocks, which

00:39:41.730 --> 00:39:43.380
is something we forget about.

00:39:43.380 --> 00:39:46.620
If your building is already
shaken by the main one,

00:39:46.620 --> 00:39:49.660
you will have many
more earthquakes to go.

00:39:49.660 --> 00:39:52.740
The building is going to have to
deal with many more earthquakes

00:39:52.740 --> 00:39:54.730
and aftershocks.

00:39:54.730 --> 00:39:56.850
And so what this
study was showing

00:39:56.850 --> 00:40:00.180
is that if you look
at those black dots,

00:40:00.180 --> 00:40:04.110
the fault is showing at
these yellow patches.

00:40:04.110 --> 00:40:07.650
The red is showing basically
the change in stress,

00:40:07.650 --> 00:40:10.680
and then you can predict
from the slip that happened

00:40:10.680 --> 00:40:12.120
on the previous earthquake.

00:40:12.120 --> 00:40:14.700
And they worked with
multiple earthquakes here.

00:40:14.700 --> 00:40:17.370
And what they found is
that the traditional way

00:40:17.370 --> 00:40:20.310
of looking at where an
earthquake would be,

00:40:20.310 --> 00:40:22.740
given a change of
stress in the crust,

00:40:22.740 --> 00:40:26.550
failed to predict many,
many of the aftershocks.

00:40:26.550 --> 00:40:30.450
But instead, they found
within your network

00:40:30.450 --> 00:40:32.910
that you could tease
out a metric, a better

00:40:32.910 --> 00:40:36.480
metric to predict where
aftershocks would be,

00:40:36.480 --> 00:40:40.110
which has to do with
stress invariance.

00:40:40.110 --> 00:40:41.820
But basically these
approaches were

00:40:41.820 --> 00:40:45.240
successful at
predicting the location

00:40:45.240 --> 00:40:47.050
of the next earthquake.

00:40:47.050 --> 00:40:49.262
And so this is
short-term forecast.

00:40:49.262 --> 00:40:51.470
It's not saying years ahead
we'll have an earthquake.

00:40:51.470 --> 00:40:53.316
It's saying we
had an earthquake,

00:40:53.316 --> 00:40:54.690
we know there will
be aftershock.

00:40:54.690 --> 00:40:57.420
And it's saying where the
next aftershock could be.

00:41:00.380 --> 00:41:02.160
Other things that
machine learning

00:41:02.160 --> 00:41:05.600
has been really successful
at in seismology

00:41:05.600 --> 00:41:09.020
is detecting those very weak,
weak ground motions that

00:41:09.020 --> 00:41:11.190
are buried in seismic noise.

00:41:11.190 --> 00:41:16.160
And it has a really
good [INAUDIBLE],,

00:41:16.160 --> 00:41:20.780
that was one of the first to use
a deep neural network to detect

00:41:20.780 --> 00:41:21.950
earthquakes.

00:41:21.950 --> 00:41:25.011
And we all worked
in Oklahoma, we

00:41:25.011 --> 00:41:27.260
worked on the data set that
already had a few thousand

00:41:27.260 --> 00:41:29.450
events, but we were
able to detect something

00:41:29.450 --> 00:41:31.280
like 20 times more events.

00:41:31.280 --> 00:41:34.010
And these are shown here,
with those beautiful S

00:41:34.010 --> 00:41:36.920
wave and P waves all aligned.

00:41:36.920 --> 00:41:40.340
And we have hundreds and
hundreds of those events

00:41:40.340 --> 00:41:42.375
that we can look at the
wave forms and say ha,

00:41:42.375 --> 00:41:43.750
actually there
was an earthquake,

00:41:43.750 --> 00:41:46.610
we just had not detected it with
natural and more established

00:41:46.610 --> 00:41:48.230
methods.

00:41:48.230 --> 00:41:51.710
And so in terms of
prediction, I think

00:41:51.710 --> 00:41:53.930
there's a lot of hope
with the new methods,

00:41:53.930 --> 00:41:57.440
and mostly the past
recording of data,

00:41:57.440 --> 00:41:59.300
where we can
potentially tease out

00:41:59.300 --> 00:42:02.300
some of these short-term
term forecasts.

00:42:02.300 --> 00:42:03.590
And I will stop here.

00:42:03.590 --> 00:42:04.400
Thank you.

00:42:04.400 --> 00:42:07.750
